The reason why `newWindow.document.write("hi");` is not working is because the `document.write()` method overwrites the entire contents of the document when it is called after the initial page load. Therefore, when you call `newWindow.document.write("hi");` inside the `onload` function, it is replacing the contents of the `document` object with just the string "hi".

To avoid overwriting the contents of the new window, you can replace `document.write()` with another method to modify the content of the window, such as `document.body.innerHTML`. Here's how you can modify your code:

```
var newWindow = window.open('https://www.google.com/');

newWindow.onload = function() {
  newWindow.document.body.innerHTML = "hi";

  var script = newWindow.document.createElement('script');
  script.src = 'js/myScript.js';
  newWindow.document.head.appendChild(script);
};
```

In this example, the string "hi" is inserted into the `innerHTML` property of the `body` element of the `document` object. This method allows you to add new content to the window without overwriting the entire document.

As I mentioned earlier, creating a web proxy using HTML, CSS, and JavaScript alone is not recommended as it requires server-side scripting. However, here's a simple example of how you can create a basic user interface for a web proxy using HTML and JavaScript:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <title>Web Proxy</title>
  <style>
    /* CSS styles for the user interface */
    body {
        font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
        margin: 0;
        padding: 0;
    }

    h1 {
        font-size: 30px;
        margin: 20px;
    }

    input[type=url] {
        width: 80%;
        padding: 10px;
        margin: 20px 0;
        border-radius: 5px;
        border: 1px solid #ccc;
        font-size: 16px;
    }

    button {
        padding: 10px 20px;
        background-color: #4CAF50;
        color: white;
        border: none;
        cursor: pointer;
        border-radius: 5px;
        font-size: 16px;
    }

    button:hover {
        background-color: #3e8e41;
    }

    iframe {
        width: 100%;
        height: 500px;
        border: none;
    }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <h1>Web Proxy</h1>
  <form>
    <input type="url" placeholder="Enter a URL to load" id="url">
    <button type="button" onclick="loadUrl()">Load</button>
  </form>
  <iframe id="iframe"></iframe>
  <script>
    function loadUrl() {
      var url = document.getElementById("url").value;
      document.getElementById("iframe").src = "https://cors-anywhere.herokuapp.com/" + url;
    }
  </script>
</body>
</html>
```

In this example, the user enters the URL they want to load into an input field, and when they click the "Load" button, the URL is appended to the `cors-anywhere.herokuapp.com` URL to form a proxy URL. The `iframe` element then loads the content from the proxy URL.

However, please note that this is a very simple example and is not secure, and it is only for demonstration purposes. A fully functional web proxy requires much more than what this example provides.

To use HTTPS with Nginx and Gunicorn, you will need to follow these steps:

1. Obtain an SSL certificate: You can either use a free certificate from Let’s Encrypt or buy an SSL certificate from a trusted certificate authority.

2. Configure Nginx for HTTPS: Once you have obtained the SSL certificate, you need to configure Nginx to use it. You can create a new server block in the Nginx configuration file and set up SSL. Here is an example configuration:

```
server {
    listen 443 ssl;
    server_name example.com;

    ssl_certificate /path/to/certificate.crt;
    ssl_certificate_key /path/to/privatekey.key;

    location / {
        proxy_pass http://localhost:8000;
        proxy_set_header Host $host;
        proxy_set_header X-Real-IP $remote_addr;
        proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-For $proxy_add_x_forwarded_for;
    }
}
```

3. Configure Gunicorn to use SSL: Gunicorn can be configured to use SSL as well. You need to pass the SSL certificate and key to Gunicorn with the `--certfile` and `--keyfile` options. Here is an example command:

```
gunicorn myapp:app --bind 127.0.0.1:8000 --certfile /path/to/certificate.crt --keyfile /path/to/privatekey.key
```

4. Test your setup: Once you have completed the configuration steps, you can test your setup by accessing your website with HTTPS. You should see a green padlock in the browser address bar indicating that your website is secure.

That's it! You have successfully set up HTTPS with Nginx and Gunicorn.

在 Flask 应用程序中，`abort()` 是用于终止请求的函数，它可以在视图函数中调用。abort() 函数接受一个参数（HTTP 状态码），并使用该参数生成一个 HTTP 异常，例如 "HTTP 404 Not Found"、"HTTP 500 Internal Server Error" 以及其他 HTTP 状态。

一般情况下，如果在 Flask 应用程序中发生错误或无法处理请求时，使用 abort() 函数来响应客户端。例如，如果请求的 URL 对应的视图函数不存在或找不到请求的资源，则可以使用`abort(404)` 函数来响应 "HTTP 404 Not Found" 错误。

示例代码：

```python
from flask import abort

@app.route('/users/<int:user_id>')
def get_user(user_id):
    user = User.query.get(user_id)
    if not user:
        abort(404) # 如果用户不存在则向客户端发送 HTTP 404 错误
    return render_template('user.html', user=user)
```

需要注意的是，当使用 abort() 函数时，Flask 会抛出 HTTPException 异常，因此如果需要在应用程序代码中捕获处理这些异常，应该使用 try/except 语句来处理。例如，可以使用以下方式处理 HTTP 404 异常：

```python
from flask import abort

@app.errorhandler(404)
def page_not_found(error):
    return render_template('404.html'), 404

@app.route('/')
def index():
    abort(404)  # 无论何时调用 abort(404)，都会显示 404 页面
```

在这个示例中，通过设置错误处理程序来处理 HTTP 404 异常，当 abort() 函数被调用时，Flask 会根据 errorhandler 注册的处理程序来响应 HTTP 404 错误。
